text: A new Ring film  is just unnecessary. Hollywood needs to give this new generation their own horror icons. Stop with the sequels, prequels, reboots of old horror movies that were perfect on their own and never needed another film in the first place and give us new stuff.  Quit with the ghost stories and unbelievable dark magic crap and go back to the basics of classics. Classic horror movies that rely on atmosphere, cinematography, music, suspense and of course Good fleshed out characters that we actually care about to bring forth the scares rather than relying on pointless and forgettable jump scares. Showing too much of the antagonist (ghost, killer etc.) leaves little to the imagination.

text: So I'm a huge fan of the original, Ringu from 1998. I feel it still is one of the scariest films ever created (along with Ju-on, The Thing etc...), and it still holds up against all the following remakes that has come out.   The first film had atmosphere, compelling story, and subtlety, (you don't even see Sadako for more then 30% of the freakin film, and she STILL managed to make me almost shit my pants!) EVERYTHING  this film doesn't seem to have:/   This is where Hollywood horror goes wrong... they think if you show some jump-cuts,  fast forwards, nudity and teenagers screaming equals FEAR, but they should learn about atmospheric horror (which is much scarier)  from the Japanese. They do it the best:)  The Annabelle 2 trailer was MUCH better then this one

text: Two major things wrong with this... sequel? remake? immediately. First is, most homes don't have landlines and if they do their phones are cordless. That girl had a flat screen television, you're asking me to believe me she has an analog phone from the 1980s. Just have the message called in on a cell phone, the movie Pulse used cell phones effectively and logically with ghosts over ten years ago. Second, even if email is still widely used it's still a bit of an outdated mode of transporting the video if their goal was to modernize the story. Would've made more sense, and been scarier, if it was a viral Youtube video or virus hidden in torrent downloads. Although I understand that may be a bit ambitious as far as writing goes, I think it would've been well worth it for a quality horror film.

text: Why would they ever make another sequel to this?  I feel like no one realizes how unbelievably bad the writing for the last two movie was.  And it looks like this one will make 90% of the same mistakes.  The outlying 10% is in regards to the fact that it is now an online video rather than a video tape.  Although this does mean that the movie will not be dated as quickly, and they can't just smash the internet like they could have, and should have done in the first movie.  (Seriously, the Characters it 'The Ring' are the dumbest in any horror movie ever).  The fact that it is online causes another large problem, however, and that is the number of people who will see the video.  Once the video is seen by enough people, and authorities link the deaths to the video, then word will be sent to the public that they will definitely die if they watch the video, then people will avoid it by the plague.  In the end, it could do more harm than good because once people know about Samara, then they can more easily avoid her evil video.   I wonder if they will actually answer the big question: Why is the girl evil?  Think about it, she was evil before her foster mother tried to drown her.  She was born evil, as is evidence by the fact that her birth mother tried to drown her.  Also, why is it that no one is capable of giving straight answers in these movies.  Think about it; there are times when the characters are supposed to have answers, but instead of giving them, they simply say some cryptic bullshit as if it is meant to explain everything.   Examples (albeit paraphrased): 'My wife was not meant to have a child'  'she never sleeps' what are these statements meant to explain?  They are stated in the first movie as it they are meant to make everything clear, but they are just creepy filler in actuality.  The Ring and the Ring 2 sucked, and they made absolutely no sense at all.
